.TH "RESTICW" "1" "" "Version 1.0" "RESTICW Usage"
.SH NAME
\f[B]resticw\f[R] \- configuration wrapper around restic
.SH SYNOPSIS
.PP
\ \f[B]resticw\f[R] <\f[B]all\f[R]|name> <cmd> [options]
.PD 0
.P
.PD
\ \f[B]resticw\f[R] <\f[B]all\f[R]|name>
<\f[B]backup\f[R]|\f[B]check\f[R]> [\f[B]\(enquiet\f[R]]
.PD 0
.P
.PD
\ \f[B]resticw\f[R] <name> <\f[B]ncdu\f[R]|\f[B]redu\f[R]>
.PD 0
.P
.PD
\ \f[B]resticw\f[R] <name> <restic pass\-through
commands/arguments\&...>
.PD 0
.P
.PD
\ \f[B]resticw\f[R] <name> \f[B]write\f[R]
\f[B]\(enexclude\-file=\f[R]<list.txt> \f[B]\(enforget\f[R]
.PD 0
.P
.PD
\ \f[B]resticw\f[R] <name> \f[B]mount\f[R] </mnt/repo>
.SH DESCRIPTION
A configuration wrapper around \f[B]restic\f[R](1).
.SS OPTIONS
.TP
name
Repository name.
.TP
\f[B]all\f[R]
Loop over all repositories.
Call \f[B]resticw\f[R] without arguments to list all repositories.
.TP
\f[B]backup\f[R]
Runs \f[B]restic backup\f[R] using the configuration files to setup
configuration arguments.
Files and directories listed in /\f[B]backup\f[R] will be included.
Files and directories in /\f[B]exclude\f[R] will be excluded.
If \f[B]backup\f[R] does not exist, this repository will be skipped for
backup but can still be used for other restic operations (e.g.\ for
remote backups stored at this location).
When \f[B]resticw\f[R] is run as root, it will drop privileges (before
running /\f[B]hook\f[R], /\f[B]env\f[R], \f[B]resticw\f[R]) except for
the \f[CR]dac_read_search\f[R] capability (read\-only access to the
whole file system).
If the /\f[B]hook\f[R] script exists, it will be executed before and
after the backup with two arguments (/\f[B]hook\f[R]
<\f[B]before\f[R]|\f[B]after\f[R]> <cmd>).
If the /\f[B]env\f[R] script exists, it will inject environment
variables.
If /\f[B]mount\f[R] exists, the path will be
\f[B]mount\f[R]/\f[B]umount\f[R] before dropping privileges.
A hook script can call other scripts or tools, but should be careful to
check for full paths and correct ownership/permisions.
If /\f[B]retention\f[R] exists, \f[B]restic forget\f[R] is used to
implement the retention policy.
Repository integrity will be confirmed using \f[B]restic check\f[R]
after all updates are complete.
.TP
\f[B]check\f[R]
Runs \f[B]restic check\f[R].
.TP
\f[B]ncdu\f[R]
Look for the largest files in the latest snapshot.
.TP
\f[B]redu\f[R]
Look for the largest files in the whole repository.
Combines all snapshots.
Allows marking files/directories into a list which can be used to update
the exclusions configuration and entirely remove files from the
repository.
See EXAMPLES.
.SH EXAMPLES
Initialize a new repository
.IP
.EX
mkdir \-p /etc/resticw/hdd
echo \(dq/mnt/hdd/backup\(dq > /etc/resticw/hdd/repo
cat /dev/urandom | tr \-dc a\-zA\-Z0\-9 | fold \-w 48 | head \-n 1 > /etc/resticw/hdd/passwd
chmod 600 /etc/resticw/hdd/passwd
chmod 644 /etc/resticw/hdd/repo
mkdir \-p /mnt/hdd/backup
chown backup:backup /mnt/hdd/backup
chmod 750 /mnt/hdd/backup
resticw hdd init
# ... add /backup config
resticw hdd backup
.EE
.PP
To permanently remove files from the repository
.PP
\f[B]resticw\f[R] <name> \f[B]rewrite\f[R]
\f[B]\(enexclude\-file=\f[R]list.txt \f[B]\(enforget\f[R]
.PP
To mount the repository, for recovering files
.PP
\f[B]resticw\f[R] <name> \f[B]mount\f[R] </mnt>
.PP
To check a repository including all the data
.PP
\f[B]resticw\f[R] <\f[B]all\f[R]|name> \f[B]check \(enread\-data\f[R]
.PP
Hook scripts can check for permission and ownership of other hook
scripts with
.IP
.EX
subhook=\(dq$(realpath $(dirname $0)/../other/hook)\(dq
[ \(dqx$(stat \-c \(aq%u:%g:%a\(aq \(dq$0\(dq)\(dq != \(dqx$(stat \-c \(aq%u:%g:%a\(aq \(dq$subhook\(dq)\(dq ] && \(rs
  echo \(dqerror: $subhook: owner & permissions must match $0\(dq 1>&2 && exit 1
.EE
.SS Best Practices
.IP \(bu 2
The classic 3\-2\-1 rule keeps three copies on two media with one
off\-site.
.IP \(bu 2
Check that backups (a) contain the right content, and (b) are still
valid.
A write\-only backup isn\(cqt worth anyone\(cqs time.
.IP \(bu 2
Data backup to the cloud \f[I]must\f[R] be encrypted at source.
Even then, don\(cqt put anything in those backups that you don\(cqt want
your grandma to see.
.IP \(bu 2
Backup frequently enough that any lost work will not hurt too much.
For example, backup of working files in the home directory might be
hourly while more static files could be weekly or monthly.
.IP \(bu 2
Cloud backups may be bandwidth limited but we still need to apply our
best practices.
.IP \(bu 2
Consider a Retention Policy as both what data needs to be protected (and
for how long) as well as what data needs to be permanently
deleted/removed after a period of time.
.SS Retention Policy
Retention Policy 24h of hourly backups, 7 daily backups, 4 weekly
backups, 12 monthly backups, 75 yearly backups
.PP
The /\f[B]retention\f[R] file format is
.IP
.EX
hourly: 24h
daily: 7d
weekly: 1m
monthly: 1y
yearly: 75y
.EE
.SS Automation
Use cron jobs to automate most of this:
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]/etc/cron.hourly/resticw\-backup\f[R]:
.PD 0
.P
.PD
\f[CR]resticw all backup \-\-quiet\f[R]
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]/etc/cron.d/resticw\-check\f[R]:
.PD 0
.P
.PD
\f[CR]20 04 11 11 * resticw all check \-\-read\-data \-\-quiet # Nov 11 \(at 04:20 (Rememberance Day)\f[R]
.SH FILES
For a particular backup <name>, the configuration files are read from
directories: /\f[B]etc\f[R]/\f[B]resticw\f[R]/<name> (global) and
\f[B]$HOME\f[R]/\f[B].config\f[R]/\f[B]resticw\f[R]/<name> (local).
Local configuration overrides global configuration.
.PP
Each <name> directory may contain files /\f[B]repo\f[R],
/\f[B]passwd\f[R], /\f[B]mount\f[R], /\f[B]env\f[R], /\f[B]backup\f[R],
/\f[B]exclude\f[R], /\f[B]retention\f[R] and /\f[B]hook\f[R].
The /\f[B]repo\f[R] and /\f[B]passwd\f[R] files are mandatory.
The remaining files are optional.
The /\f[B]hook\f[R] and /\f[B]env\f[R] scripts are executable.
Any other files in the directory are ignored.
.PP
Rules for the ownership and visibility of configuration files is
enforced for security.
(Or at least reduced finger fudges.)
All files must be chmod go\-wx.
The /\f[B]passwd\f[R] and /\f[B]env\f[R] files must be chmod go\-rwx.
The owner of the /\f[B]passwd\f[R] file must be the current user.
All files in the directory must have the same owner.
Files in the configuration can be links, in which case the ownership
rule applies to the linked file (see \f[B]realpath\f[R](1)).
Repositories without a /\f[B]backup\f[R] file are skipped during
\f[B]resticw backup\f[R].
